Faris Eltayib edited to: “It's all based on your personal interests tbh. If you're interested in networking or social networks, then go for it. It's not that bad of a class, I just didn't particularly enjoy the subject or assignments; but the workload was really manageable. The only time consuming thing was the final project which is group dependent (if you get a good group, it's easygoing and vice versa)

I haven't taken 348, but I think you spend the first half learning about AI and the next half learning about some ML algorithms. It's definitely easier than 349. In 349 you learn a ton of ml algorithms, so it's pretty dense but really informative (and no exams!)”

text: I’ve watched the rain’s silver fingers tap out a symphony of chaos, drenching me like a surprise baptism. Sidewalks become moist, sending commuters flailing like startled geese, their dignity slipping with each soggy step. As raindrops seep into my collar, I’m reminded: even the grandest plans can dissolve into wilted napkins in a single downpour — yet there’s a strange comfort in knowing that if life’s troubles can be washed away so easily, my mop of frizzy hair and soaked shoes are badges of honor in weather’s mischievous performance.

Hey everyone! So I'm part of a club called FutureDev and in case you haven't heard of it we focus on providing mentorship for those interested in web, game, and app development. This quarter we only have mentors for web and game dev. Currently our signups are open to be placed into one of our groups and learn about your area of choice to then create a small culminating project guided by your mentor. To see what our mentors have planned, you can check out their outlines in the following linktree. The link to sign up is also in the linktree. name: Ethan Pineda
text:
Also going to push back on the notion of “real” classes. Every professor and course has a different approach and teaching philosophy. If you don’t like it, then you don’t have to take the class. 

Also taking more “real classes” != better engineer. Sone of the best people I’ve met in industry have never taken OS for example. 

Let’s not promote these ideas in our community

name: Ethan Pineda
text:
This is just some info about how summer classes work. 

it’s completely ad-hoc, so it only depends on people in the department who want to teach a class over the summer. That’s why for example 214, we haven’t had it taught over the past 2 summers because the one person willing to do it graduated. 

From a professor standpoint, the only benefit for teaching a class is earning some side income for the summer. Teaching staff are only contracted to teach 6 sections a quarter so that’s why you’ll probably never someone like Braden of Vincent teach during the summer cause they hit their quotas during the school year 

This is also why you mostly see PhD students teach summer classes, ramping up their teaching experiences and resumes before applying to jobs

text: ^ I second this. Design principles and methods can seem really obvious when you hear about them for the first time, but having worked with professional designers before, I can tell you that genuinely so much thought and iteration goes into every decision you make from the colors and fonts you use to the layouts of whole web pages. I feel like HCI is a really easy topic to brush aside as basic or easy, but I personally think it does a really important job of tying back into why we develop things in the first place :) after all, you could put dozens of hours into making your code high quality, but it doesn’t end up mattering if the design the code is implementing isn’t actually useful, intuitive, and accessible

name: Omar Sharaf
text:
The gist:
WHO
* TIDAL Lab and tiilt lab, in partnership with the School of Education and Social Policy and Department of Computer Science
* Evanston/Skokie School District 65
* You!

WHAT
* Volunteer to work in local 5th grade Computer Science (CS) classrooms
* Help support student self-expression and critical thinking in a novel CS learning environment 
* Approximately 3-5 hours/week time commitment

WHEN
* Apply here by Monday, October 14 at 11:59 PM
* Program dates: January 7, 2025 - June 5, 2025 (Winter and Spring quarters)

WHY
* Opportunity to give back to your community
* Earn course credit (optional)
* Looks great on your resume
* Good for your soul

Please direct any questions to Nick LaGrassa (they/them) (nick.lagrassa@u.northwestern.edu) with the subject line “D65 Volunteer Opportunity”.

name: Omar Sharaf
text:
Dear students,

Do you enjoy helping others learn and discover? Do you believe self-expression and student voice should be centered in classrooms? Do you enjoy music and/or athletics? If you answered ‘yes' to any of these questions, we encourage you to apply for our program!

This winter and spring we have a volunteer opportunity to work in local 5th grade computer science classrooms. Volunteers may choose to earn an optional credit alongside this commitment. Please review the information below for a summary of the opportunity and see the attached PDF for a more detailed job description. All Northwestern students are encouraged to apply!

Hi all, it’s great to announce that we are starting our Fall 2024 rush process for PGN, a national business fraternity founded in Northwestern 100 years ago!

text: We are currently developing a course to take members from not knowing anything about programming and hardware, to building their own game controller from scratch (to play a game I made) over the course of 6ish weeks. It is a fun opportunity if you want to learn about cpp and embedded development.

name: Evan Bertis-Sample
text: If you want tangible experience with Cpp, I would also recommend joining Northwestern Formula Racing (kind of a self plug here lol). We use Cpp for all of our firmware. Last year, my project involved building my own wireless communication protocol (which ended up with me building my own programming language  somehow) using Cpp powered the Car's wireless telemetry system. We have lots of fun projects, ranging in complexity

name: Evan Bertis-Sample
text: In CS 397/497, Wireless Protocols for IoT we used C and Cpp to do embedded stuff. CS 346 Microprocessor System Design might also use Cpp. If they ever offer CS 351-2 again, Intermediate Computer Graphics, I believe they used Cpp and openGL.

text: 376 is a pretty chill class, except for the exams, you highkey need to study for them and there’s a decent amount of material that’s covered

name: Evan Bertis-Sample
text: Both 376 and 377 are 10/10 classes imo, albeit, I might be biased as I've been gunning for game dev/graphics programming as a career for a fat minute

name: Evan Bertis-Sample
text: Also brush up on data structures like trees and graphs. Most of 376 is pretty conceptual, and it will give you an overview of how game engines work under the hood, and how the design process for game dev is like

name: Evan Bertis-Sample
text: Ian is the goat for 376. Make sure you are familiar with basic linear Algebra, like matrix transformations and vectors. Also make sure you are familiar with C# or languages adjacent to C#, like Java or C++. The class is pretty easy, as long as you don't fall behind. If you choose to take 377, then make sure to allocate some extra time for the class in the winter, especially if you want to make a cool game.

name: Safiya Menk
text:
EMCO Community,

As FGLI students, we have witnessed and experienced the struggle to obtain resources that students need to thrive and survive in institutions such as Northwestern.

This is nothing in comparison to what we are witnessing in Gaza. There are Palestinians with no resources, no help, and no opportunity to obtain the privileged education we currently have due their universities being destroyed and thousands being killed and displaced.

Moving forward, Emerging Coders will hold all events that we are able to at Deering Lawn, for as long as the encampment continues. We encourage our community to use their voices to support Gaza and spread the word for a Free Palestine. We encourage our community to support the demands in the Northwestern People’s Resolution.

Support the encampment as much as you can. But we will remind you to please prioritize your safety as well and protect those around you.

Emerging Coders Exec

Calling all CS upperclassmen with internship experience! DISC will be hosting an “Internship Insider Panel” featuring upperclassmen who have navigated technical internships across a diverse set of roles and industries, including but not limited to app/web/game development, cybersecurity, systems, data science, product management, software engineering, and UI/UX design. 

As panelists, we would ask you to share insights into the day-to-day realities of your internship. We would ask questions like how to overcome imposter syndrome, how to make the most out of an internship, and how to secure a return offer. 

If you would be willing to participate in this event as a panelist, please fill out this interest form: https://forms.gle/YVnA4fM7mHHuqpzv5. Thank you for your time and consideration!

text:
Hey guys, I'm an alum and machine learning engineer that lives in Evanston. I also am a volunteer at Code Nation, which is a NFP focused on training high school students from underrepresented groups to get careers in tech [0].

I asked Amiin to add me to this group because we could use a Spanish speaking volunteer in one of our classes in Rogers Park (Amiin just started with us this January). If you are interested & available from 930-11 Mondays and Wednesdays please DM. Transportation (me) will be provided.

Code Nation has a ton of volunteers that are engineers at tech companies across the country and there are great networking opportunities in addition to serving the community!

Thank you
Fahad

name: Blanka Jarmoszko (she/her)
text: As for useful YouTube channels: NeetCode has a lot of walk throughs problems. I also like FreeCodeCamp.org , they have long videos that go over most common problems for each topic

name: Blanka Jarmoszko (she/her)
text: Also I would say try to do problems in the same topic for a bit so you can learn the patterns of the solutions. Once those click write them down then you have a little cheat sheet

name: Omotayo Oludemi
text: Okay

name: Blanka Jarmoszko (she/her)
text: Also I would say for leetcode, try a brute force approach first and see if you can get it to run properly. Then try thinking about ways you could get it to be better and more efficient. If you feel stuck after 10ish minutes watch YouTube videos that walk you through it and before they show the code try going back and implementing it yourself. That’s just something that worked well for me

An example would be like if you had the array [1,3,5,7,9] and your goal is to find the max sum of two consecutive numbers. So in this case, your sliding window has a size of 2. These are your windows: 

[1,3], [3,5], [5,7], [7,9] 

So basically each iterate computes the sum of the window for this problem and the solution is 16

name: Ethan Pineda
text: Imagine you have an array (or a string, which is essentially an array of characters). The "sliding window" is a sub-array (or sub-string) of this array, which "slides" from the beginning of the array to the end. The window has a fixed size, which determines how many elements it includes at any given time.

text: In a singly linked-list (like the one you described and you will learn on day 1 of 214) each node in the SLL has two parts: a data field (which stores the specific value like 1) and a reference to the next node in the linked-list. text:
Hey everyone! 

With our club website fully published and operational, it's time to open up the doors for folks to contribute to it! We currently have a list of ideas for things we want to implement/change about the website on both the frontend and backend. Main things right now involve fixing broken links, redesigning some of the pages, and adding more functionality and improving performance and doing a whole codebase refactor among other things [NO EXPERIENCE REQUIRED, JUST MOTIVATION TO LEARN AND CONTRIBUTE!]

And for those curious, here is out tech stack
- React 
- TypeScript (I want to move the codebase to TS) 
- Next.js (app router) 
- Tailwind CSS
- NextUI
- Node/Express
- Vercel
- Supabase

If this is something that interest you, feel free to DM me on groupme or instagram (@ethan.paneraa) and we can setup a time to meet.

name: Erick Mungai
text:
Here’s my biased opinion

CS339 w/ Prof Rogers - the ctecs are bad but i promise its not a bad class. Imo this is one of the most important CS classes. Just show up to class everyday. Hws, projects and exams are not that bad. She gives extra credit for participating in class which is great for offsetting any points you lose
CS340 - super useful esp if you ever do a system design interview. Can never go wrong with it 
CS343 w/ Branden - useful for learning things like concurrency which is super useful for the job. Has alot of extra credit so its easy to make up for lost points. Just dont take it with Dinda or you’ll struggle 😂
CS349,449 - Does it really hurt to learn ML and deep learning?
CS310 - As many have said. Great class for tangible experience 
CS321 w/ Vincent

If you enjoy CE 
CE346
CE303
CE361 w/ Russ - You build processors for the class. Cool stuff

name: Evan Bertis-Sample
text: I totally agree with CS 310, especially if you want go into any backend development. I'm super jealous of people in CE 346 -- it's a really good class to take for firmware stuff. CS 340 really removes the black box that is computer networking, and teaches super useful ideas for communication protocol, which can be used even outside of network programming. CS 330 is an okay class -- it's like DTC 3 for CS people. I personally didn't enjoy it, even as a design oriented person. I've heard good things about CS 343, but that's mainly from systems people.

name: John Sanchez
text: I would also look into cs393/cs394, I havent taken the classes but from what my friends have told me you learn how to build something from the ground up. Also doesn't seem like TOO much of a commitment (whatever you put into your project you get out)

name: Ethan Pineda
text:
Only really know CS classes but this is what i would recommend off top of my head 

CE 346 (braden goated + im so sad i couldn't get in this quarter) 
CS 310 (projects aren't bad + good to learn AWS, JS, TS, Node & Express for industry) 
Can't go wrong with any of the HCI classes (330, 313, 329 etc) 
CS 343 (Hard but i've heard a lot its good to know for internships) 
CS 348 w/ Alam highkey not that bad, but if you want to learn more, take it with Rubenstein imo 
CS 394 also good for building a good project for resume
I'm personally not a big of game dev but I went through the sequence of 376 and 377, 376 was decent it was jus the exams 377 was easy if u have a good group (do the sequence with a group of friends imo) 
CS 396: Ethics was most chillest class but also very informative and unique class

text:
Are you a junior or a senior looking for a job? This event is perfect for you!

EPIC, Northwestern’s entrepreneurship club, is excited to host a Business Strategy Workshop with Clipboard Health Thursday, May 25th, at 3 PM! Clipboard Health (YC W17) is an app-based marketplace that connects healthcare facilities and healthcare professionals, allowing healthcare professionals to book on-demand shifts and healthcare facilities to access on-demand talent. EPIC will be taking students to join Clipboard Health in a customer discovery workshop on May 25th from 3 pm - 6 pm, where students will interview real customers and create investment memos and business strategy recommendations. Top-performing teams will receive priority consideration for Clipboard Health’s internship and full-time roles: https://boards.greenhouse.io/clipboardhealth?t=b2e829504us 

We will wrap up with dinner with the Clipboard team at 6:00 pm!

Don't have an internship lined up for the summer? Check out Data Science 4 All/Women Program with Correlation One!
Who can apply:
DS4A / Women is intended for people who identify as women. At present, the program is open only to candidates who can legally reside and work in the United States.
Basics about the program:
7 weeks of class with a team capstone project
Requires a 10 hour per week commitment for work outside of class
Training in Data Analytics
Networking with leaders in data fields & other talented professionals
Mentoring from a network of professional mentors who work in data
Live online training with a schedule built for busy students & professionals
Jobs from top companies, like Accenture & BlackRock
For free! The program is sponsored by our Employer Partners

Link: https://www.correlation-one.com/data-science-for-all-women?utm_source=amb&utm_medium=amb&utm_campaign=KELL
Deadline: May 7th

name: Ethan Pineda
text:
Hey everyone! If you/or someone that you know is a second-year looking to break into tech as Software Engineer, I encourage y'all to apply for Management Leadership for Tomorrow's Software Engineering track. It's a an amazing opportunity and experience to be a part of and it'll definitely help out with getting your foot through the door and secure the internship/job offer of your dreams! A lot of the upperclassmen I've connected who are going/have gone through the program speak only positive things about the experience and have gotten the chance to work at some pretty amazing companies.

I'm happy to speak to anyone about the application process/even give a referral since the folks at MLT want to see more NU students in the program!! Here is a link to recruitment resources as well: https://info.mlt.org/cp-recruiting-resources
